lt may beas well to state brietiy the rules of intestate succession where the deceased was a filiusfamilias with peculium oran emancipatus. In respect of peculium adventitium, Theodosius and Valentinian enacted that (r) bona materna should go to the pater, (2) lucra nuptialia to the children of the deceased filiusfamilias, the pater having the usufruct for life : in default of children to the pater, and falling him to brothers aud sisters. Leo and Anthemius postponed the pater to brothers and sisters, even of the half blood. Justinian extended these rules relating to lucra nuptialia to bona matema and materni generis in their integrity, Cod. 6. 59. 11, and later still to all peculium adventitium from whatever source derived.

For the earlier law relating to peculium castrense see on Bk. ito pr. supr. ln Justinian’s time brothers and sisters as well as children of the deceased were preferred to the pater (Bk. ii. 12. pr. supr. ‘si vero in· testati decesserint, nullis liberis vel fratribus superstitibus, ad parentes eorum iure communi pertinebit :' cf. Cod. 6. 61. 3 and 4), who took the peculium only if there were none to precede him. The same rules governed the succession to peculium quasi castrense.
